Prep the tomatoes and potatoes: Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Thinly slice the @Yukon Gold Potatoes{24%ounce} (you can keep the skin on) into 1/8-inch thick rounds, like chips. Thinly slice the @Roma Tomato{4} into rounds.

Toss the potato rounds on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @Olive Oil{2%tablespoon}, @Garlic Powder{2%teaspoon}, and a pinch of @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Place in the oven for ~{15-20%minutes}, flipping halfway through cooking, until golden brown.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the @Ground Beef{16%ounce}, 4 Tablespoons @BBQ Sauce{2%jar}, and the remaining garlic powder. Form the mixture into four patties about the size of the buns. Season each patty generously with salt and pepper.

With about 10 minutes left on the potatoes, heat a large drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the patties to the pan and cook for ~{2-4%minutes} per side, until almost cooked to desired doneness. Place the @Cheddar Cheese{1%cup} on top of the patties, cover, and cook for another ~{1%minute}, until melted.

While the burgers cook, split the @Potato Buns{4} and place in the oven to toast for about ~{5%minutes}. Toss the @Mixed Greens{4%ounce} in a medium bowl with a large drizzle of oil and a pinch of salt and pepper.

Assemble the burgers: Spread the toasted buns with the remaining BBQ sauce and fill with the patties, tomatoes, and a bit of spring mix. Serve the potato chips with the @Ketchup{1%jar} for dipping, and any remaining spring mix to the side. Enjoy!

> Making baked potato chips is such a breeze; you'll never buy them from the store again!

> A touch of sweet and smoky barbecue sauce goes right into the burgers for an unexpected twist.